Vheadline
p2
VSongs for sport
p3
sVnews
p4
VWith a number of musicians vying to pep up India's spirits during the Commonwealth Games, classical as well as popular music exponents are vying for your ear. Among them is Madhur Lata, an exponent of Hindustani music who heads the organisation Jai Bharat. Jai Bharat has released an audio CD with a welcome song, &#8220;Shubh Agaman&#8221; and another, &#8220;Ao Khelein Khel&#8221;. The songs, says Madhur Lata, who has composed both music and lyrics, are intended to convey &#8220;Indian colour and fervour.&#8221; While the welcome song is based on raga Bhupali, the second one is &#8220;based on the notes of Madhuvanti,&#8221; she explains.Meanwhile, yet another song joined the jamboree when Raman Kapoor, a businessman-turned-singer, unveiled his song &#8220;Shubhankar&#8221; at the India Habitat Centre the other day.&#8220;Shubhankar' means mascot, explains the singer, and it is a five-minute musical tribute to the Games. The lyrics are by Vishvjit, and Balvinder Assie has provided the tune.Kapoor has two albums to his credit. Music, he believes, is the perfect medium to reach out to the masses.The song will be put on air by All India Radio as part of its showcasing of the Commonwealth Games and on Radio Dhamal. The song will also be uploaded on websites like YouTube.
